 Alaska port cities and at Bellingham Washington 1 Five million rural residents live outside of the service areas of all three intercity modes Connecticut Delaware Massachusetts New Jersey and Rhode Island are the only states in which every resident lives within the service area of at least one mode What is a transportation service area A Bureau of Transportation Statistics BTS 2003 study defines it as the 25 mile area surrounding a nonhub or small hub airport an intercity rail station or an intercity bus terminal For large or medium hub airports a 75 mile area was used The study found Intercity bus service reaches 91 percent 75 million of the rural population and is the sole mode for 15 million people 2 Endnote 2 There is no scheduled intercity bus service in Alaska and Hawaii although year round scheduled vans or minibuses serve seven communities between Fairbanks Anchorage and Seward AK 2 Scheduled airline service reaches 70 percent 58 million of the rural population and is the only mode for 2 million rural residents Scheduled intercity passenger rail service reaches 42 percent 35 million and is the sole mode for more than 300 000 people 3 Endnote 3 There is no scheduled intercity rail service in Hawaii 3 Thirty six 36 percent 30 million of the rural population live within the service area for all three modes A series of maps showing the locations of intercity transportation facilities across the United States by mode accompanies this study The maps show the proximity of those facilities to rural areas html rural areas served by scheduled intercity bus html Rural Areas Served by Scheduled Intercity Bus html rural areas served by scheduled airlines html Rural Areas Served by Scheduled Airlines html rural areas served by scheduled airlines in alaska and hawaii html Rural Areas Served by Scheduled Airlines in Alaska and Hawaii html rural areas served by scheduled intercity rail html Rural Areas Served by Scheduled Intercity Rail html rural areas served by scheduled 